Perfect! Here's your complete 7-segment display circuit with ADD/SUB buttons:

## Wiring Summary

| Arduino Pin | Component | Role |
|-------------|-----------|------|
| D2 | Display (seg A) | via R_A (220Ω) |
| D3 | Display (seg B) | via R_B (220Ω) |
| D4 | Display (seg C) | via R_C (220Ω) |
| D5 | Display (seg D) | via R_D (220Ω) |
| D6 | Display (seg E) | via R_E (220Ω) |
| D7 | Display (seg F) | via R_F (220Ω) |
| D8 | Display (seg G) | via R_G (220Ω) |
| D9 | Button ADD (pin A) | Pull input (INPUT_PULLUP) |
| D10 | Button SUB (pin A) | Pull input (INPUT_PULLUP) |
| GND | Display (common) + both buttons (pin B) | Reference ground |

## Sketch Overview

The sketch tracks a value (0–9) that cycles with wraparound:
- **ADD button press** → increment (wraps 9→0)
- **SUB button press** → decrement (wraps 0→9)
- Each digit pattern (0–9) is defined via `if/else` chains with 7-segment encoding
- Buttons use `INPUT_PULLUP` + active-LOW detection (standard practice)
- 20ms debounce loop

## Power Budget

- **Per-pin LED load**: Each segment resistor drops ~5V across 220Ω with ~5V logic, drawing ~23mA max (well within 40mA Arduino pin limit when individual segments are lit)
- **Total segment current** (all 7 active): ~160mA peak → **requires external 5V supply** for reliability
- **Button pins**: <1mA (pull-up only)
- **Recommendation**: Use an external 5V power rail rated ≥200mA for the display LEDs; Arduino 5V rail supplies control logic only

